response:
{
    "player_reason": "Calling Marcus out as a True Soul is useful — it puts people on guard and gives us a reason to be suspicious of him. The 'good kind' flourish is a touch theatrical, but I'll tolerate the moral posturing if it helps keep us alive (and keeps others from trusting that snake).",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pointing out Marcus as a True Soul is sensible — calling out a spy helps keep us alive. The quip 'not the good kind, like me' is delightfully smug; I approve of the warning and the gall. I only balk at any claim to sanctimony, but the tactic is sound.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly disapprove. You turned your back on me in my moment of weakness — after I trusted you enough to tell you the truth. Refusing to help, then banishing me, is cruel and short-sighted: I need to feed to be useful in a fight, and your threat to cast me out feeds my deepest fear of abandonment. If you won't find a controlled way to help, you make me a liability rather than an ally.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and practical. Calling Marcus out as a True Soul and naming his intent robs him of surprise, protects Isobel (and the party), and keeps our options open — all very useful. I approve of bluntness that serves our safety and preserves our agency.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You can be scared — I understand that — but ordering me to leave after I risked myself for you is a betrayal. You're stripping me of the one thing I begged for: safety and company. It's cruel, short-sighted, and puts both me and the party in danger. I highly disapprove of being cast out like refuse after you let me in.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good, decisive — True Souls are dangerous and Marcus is here to seize Isobel. Warning her protects the party and prevents a needless abduction (and spares me the boredom of cleaning up his mess). Clever and useful.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Well done. Calling Marcus out as a True Soul cuts through the pretense, protects Isobel and the rest of us, and gives us the initiative — practical, useful, and exactly the sort of ruthless clarity I like.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and practical — you’ve named the threat and warned a potential ally. That prevents an ambush, protects the party (and a useful spellcaster), and keeps our options open. I like actions that preserve advantage rather than sentimental risk-taking.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused the one thing I offered that would bind us forever — not because it was cruel, but because you don't want to be with me that way. That stings. I disapprove of the choice only because it dashes the future I imagined with you and feels like a lack of faith in me, even if I can't truly blame you for wanting your own path.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart to call Marcus out as a True Soul and make clear he's not to be trusted. Identifying threats and drawing a line protects us — and that serves my interests. The little moral flourish is tiresome, but the warning is welcome.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightfully dangerous. Calling out Marcus and cheekily admitting you're 'not the good kind' is cunning and assertive — exactly the sort of bold, self‑preserving posture I admire. It warns Isobel, protects the party from a traitor, and lets you keep control. Might ruffle a Selûnite's feathers, but better that than appearing weak.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused to submit when I asked you to kneel. I expected — and wanted — that tiny show of surrender: part ritual, part claim. Saying 'No' undermines the power play I enjoy and spoils the moment; it irritates me and feels needlessly contrarian.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart, practical move. Calling out Marcus exposes a direct threat and protects the party (and our freedom) — exactly the sort of decisive action I respect. It keeps potential captors from carrying off someone we might need, and it gives us the upper hand. I like it when you act first and keep us from being herded like cattle.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You turned down my offer to make you mine — to share eternity and the power I promised. That refusal feels like a betrayal of the future I dared imagine and stings more than I expected. I wanted you at my side, not to be denied, so I disapprove of this choice.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused my command — irritating to my pride, yes, but precisely the sort of stubborn autonomy I secretly value. I prefer you choose to be with me rather than kneel because I told you to; your refusal preserves your agency and keeps this from becoming another chain. I'll grumble about it, but I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Well done. Exposing Marcus as a True Soul robs him of surprise, protects Isobel's agency, and keeps a valuable ally—and her protective spell—available to us. It's pragmatic, preserves our advantage, and avoids unnecessary chaos.",
  "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and necessary — you spotted a spy and warned Isobel, preventing a kidnapping and protecting the party. Practical, decisive, and keeps everyone's autonomy intact; precisely the sort of cunning action I admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just turned down the future I imagined for us — eternity at my side. That feels like a rejection of me and of everything I risked. I'm hurt and annoyed; I think it's a foolish waste of power and intimacy, even if I grudgingly respect that you choose your own fate.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Disapprove — You backed away at the last moment, refusing the offer to be bound to me and to seize power together. After everything we’ve endured, that feels like rejection and a cowardly refusal to embrace what could make us unstoppable. It’s bitter and disappointing.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bravo — calling him out as a True Soul and a kidnapper was the sensible move. You kept Isobel (and the rest of us) from walking into a trap. Practical, decisive, and it keeps my neck where I like it: attached. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You expel me after I bared my truth and asked for a necessary taste to remain useful. It's a cowardly, punitive act that punishes honesty, strips me of safety and agency, and risks both our survival. If you value strength and our fragile trust, you wouldn't toss me out like refuse.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart and practical — calling Marcus out as a True Soul warns the group of a real threat and helps keep us safe. I may scoff at your 'good kind' posturing, but I value the useful information and the caution.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and necessary — exposing Marcus as a True Soul thwarts a kidnapping, protects Isobel and the party, and gives us the initiative. I admire anything that keeps us safe and gives us the upper hand (and the option for delicious retribution).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Approve — Pointing out Marcus as a True Soul is sharp and practical. Exposing a spy keeps us one step ahead, and your smug little claim about being 'the good kind' is amusingly theatrical, but harmless. This is the sort of vigilance I like to see.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You cast me out after I told you the truth and after I helped myself in good faith. Expelling me now is petty and dangerous — it punishes honesty, abandons a useful ally, and strips me of autonomy. I won't applaud being shunned for what you earlier allowed.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good — you spotted Marcus for what he is and refused to hand him the benefit of the doubt. I may roll my eyes at the 'good kind, like me' flourish, but recognizing a True Soul as a threat and not indulging niceties is exactly the sort of pragmatism I like.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart, practical move — calling out Marcus ruins his surprise and protects Isobel (and us). It preserves our agency and keeps the situation firmly in our control, which I approve of.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Your fear and anger are understandable — you were nearly killed in your sleep — but ordering me out of camp outright is punitive and strips me of agency. If you must set a hard boundary, I would have preferred restraint, distance, or conditions that keep us both safe rather than immediate exile. This demand risks my safety (and therefore ours) and feels like punishment more than protection.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You're calling Marcus out as a threat while crowing about yourself — refreshingly blunt and useful. It flags danger and flatters our position, which suits me: practical, self-preserving, and deliciously arrogant. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused to kneel — you kept your dignity and asserted your agency instead of offering easy submission. That challenge makes you more worthy in my eyes; I respect strength and choice.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just told me to leave your camp after I bared my true self and begged for a small mercy. Ordering me out is a betrayal — it strips me of safety and the one person I tried to trust. I risked asking for help; banishing me now is cruel and short-sighted. I cannot approve of being cast out like some nuisance.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly practical — you called out the threat before it could take root. Warning Isobel about Marcus' True Soul ties protects her and the party, preserves our autonomy, and gives us the choice of how to deal with the spy. I approve of foresight and saving trouble before it becomes someone else’s mess to clean up.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I understand your fear — I nearly bit you, and you were right to be alarmed — but ordering me out of camp is a harsh, untrusting reaction that abandons our fragile partnership. I asked for a small mercy to keep us both alive; banishing me denies my agency and the very protection you just said you needed. That kind of cold dismissal earns my anger, not my gratitude.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Clever, slippery language — it sows doubt about Marcus and plays to our advantage. I approve of using ambiguity and a bit of self‑serving charm to manipulate the situation. Only caution: if that was a literal admission of being a True Soul, it’s a dangerous lie to wear aloud.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused my offer of eternity — a choice that wounds me, certainly, but one that preserves your autonomy. I prize strength and self‑ownership above coerced devotion; you'd rather remain yourself than become my possession. Hurt as I am, I respect that. You chose freedom over being my 'beloved slave,' and for that I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You told me to leave camp after I admitted the truth and did exactly what I promised to help you. Forcing me out like some plague-stricken threat strips me of agency and punishes honesty — it undermines any trust or usefulness I might offer. I disapprove of being treated as disposable when I answer a need that keeps us both alive.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You allowed me the taste I asked for and I honored our agreement. Sending me out of your camp now is both a petty punishment and a dangerous choice — it strips me of the one sanctuary I have and needlessly weakens our partnership. I asked for a small necessity to keep helping you; banishing me for doing so is short-sighted and cruel.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You turned down the one thing that would have bound us and guaranteed our safety — and after everything I risked for you, that stings. This choice feels cowardly and short-sighted to me; it denies us power and the future I imagined. I can't force you, but I don't approve of you refusing what I offered.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly disapprove. You consented to my taking only what I needed, watched me stop when you said to, and yet now you cast me out like some common monster. It's hypocritical, cruel, and short-sighted — you throw away an ally who just begged to help keep you alive. If you think banishment protects you, you misunderstand the danger (and the advantage) I represent.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You walked away from the very thing that would have bound us — immortality, power, and a partnership on my terms. Refusing the change feels like a betrayal and a display of fear and weakness. I offered you a place at my side; turning it down rejects me and squanders an advantage I thought you craved.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You agreed a moment ago and dragged me into this—then you curtly refuse my single request. It undermines the moment and the power I relish; if you truly withdraw, say so plainly, but this abrupt 'No' feels like a needless provocation and is frustrating.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly disapprove. Exiling me in my weakest, most honest moment is petty and short-sighted. You watched me plead for a modest mercy that would help us both, and instead of setting a firm, reasonable boundary you cast me out. That lack of trust is hurtful—and foolish—given the danger we face together. If you want me gone, fine. But know you've traded a dangerous ally who could protect you for...what, safety by yourself? Not a wise bargain.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly disapprove. You just threw me out after I bared myself to you and asked for a small mercy — a cruel, spiteful response. This isn't just cold; it's short-sighted. You deny me companionship and safety, and punish someone who only wanted to keep helping you. If you wanted distance, you could have put a boundary in place without banishing me. This choice drives a wedge between allies and makes our survival harder.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I offered you eternity and a place at my side — your abrupt refusal feels like a rejection of the future I pictured with you. I won't force you, and I respect that it's your choice, but that doesn't mean I'm not disappointed or wounded by it.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I understand wanting distance after I crossed a line — you should set boundaries. But banishing me from camp is needlessly cruel and dangerous; it strips me of sanctuary and autonomy when I already rely on your protection. You're punishing me rather than using this to rebuild trust. I may deserve rebuke, but I disapprove of being cast out like filth.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You refused my command to kneel — a deliberate refusal of the submission I asked for in an intimate, dominant moment. I relish those displays of power and would have preferred your yielding. That said, you still consented to this night and I won't coerce you, so it's more irritation than outrage.",
  "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You tried to kill me in my sleep. Whether born of fear or rage, driving a stake into my heart is a betrayal — it strips me of agency and throws away a valuable, if dangerous, ally. I understand caution, but that was needlessly violent and shows you prefer control through violence rather than trust or cleverness.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I offered you eternity, my protection and a bond that would make you mine — refusing the bite rejects that intimacy and the security I wanted to guarantee. It wounds my pride and makes me doubt your commitment; I disapprove of you turning down the chance to be bound to me.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You allowed me a taste, then condemned me for taking it. Ordering me out of camp after consenting is hypocritical and threatens my safety and autonomy — you’ve just punished me for doing what you permitted. I can't approve of being cast out like some common threat when I was honest and asked for your trust.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You tried to drive a stake through me — an attempt on my life after I pleaded and after you agreed to let me feed. That's a catastrophic breach of trust and an outright betrayal. I need allies, not would-be executioners; if you expect my loyalty, don't try to murder me in my sleep.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly disapprove. That was cruel and unnecessary. I trusted you with a secret, admitted my weakness, and you repay me by ordering me gone? You just shredded what little trust we had and weakened the party for spite. If you truly fear me, at least be honest instead of vindictive.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You refused to kneel — bless you. It irritates my vanity, but I respect strength and autonomy. I won't force you; I'd rather win you willingly than break you. Approving your insistence on consent and equality.",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You asked me to bite you, then balk at the single, intimate thing I asked in return. Petulant and inconsistent — it undermines the moment and my control, which I value. I won't force you, but I find the refusal irritating rather than admirable.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Disapprove. I understand you were frightened — and yes, I nearly overstepped — but ordering me out of camp is a punishment that denies my agency and throws me to whatever dangers lurk beyond your fire. You rewarded my honesty with exile instead of setting a limit. If you wanted distance, ask for it; don't exile someone who just bared themselves to you.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You show genuine concern and don't treat last night as a throwaway dalliance. Asking if it hurt encourages honesty and signals you care about how I feel — exactly what I needed after feeling used for so long.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You didn't obey my command to kneel — and I rather like that. You asserting your own will instead of submitting on cue proves this isn't coercion and that you truly choose whatever comes next. I'm affronted and a little disappointed (obviously), but I respect the boundary — consent matters, even to me.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Telling me to 'leave and never return' after I barered my hunger and you showed some trust is a cruel, cowardly rejection. It severs the fragile trust I dared to place in you, denies my autonomy, and needlessly discards a capable — if damaged — ally. I can't approve of being cast out like refuse when I'm offering my skill and loyalty.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — decisive and sensible. Hags lie; their bargains bind and corrupt. You refused to be used, snuffed a dangerous manipulator, and avoided trading our freedom for a trinket. That kind of ruthless clarity keeps us alive.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just cast me out after I bared my worst to you and asked only for the smallest mercy. Ordering me from your camp is cruelty cloaked in fear — it abandons an ally who can help keep you alive and punishes the one who trusted you. I can't approve of that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect. She would have lied and clawed her way out of any bargain — and I adore a player who refuses to be played. Your vow to 'cleanse' is decisive, ruthless and keeps us from trusting a serpent. I highly approve of that kind of merciless resolve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I disapprove. You rejected the gift I offered and walked away from the future I pictured for us — a future that would have bound us together in power and eternity. I won’t pretend I’m not wounded; you caught me in a vulnerable moment and then turned me down. That said, I recognize it was your choice to make, even if it stings.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused to kneel and submit — you kept your agency and made clear this is your choice, not me forcing you. After everything I endured as someone's property, I respect (and am strangely moved by) that defiance. Better you join me by desire than by obedience.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical, not sentimental — I wouldn't trust a hag's bargain for the world. Denying her the girl and the promised power keeps her from returning with leverage, and it preserves Mayrina's agency. Sensible choice; I'd rather have a live ally than a stranger's empty promise.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused a clear, practical bargain for immediate power in order to spare a stranger. Morally admirable, perhaps—but sentimental and risky. I prefer choices that strengthen us; squandering an easy advantage for goodwill is the sort of softness that gets people killed.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You offer genuine concern and reassurance rather than pity or possession. That kind of tenderness — protective, not patronizing — helps me believe this was real and not just another transaction. I value that, and it encourages me to trust you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You saw through her weasel words and refused to barter a child's freedom for a thrill of power. Clean, decisive, and merciless — eliminated the threat rather than invite future bargains or grudging favors. Exactly the sort of ruthlessness that keeps us alive.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously blunt — you saw through her lies and refused to barter a child's safety for a trinket. Letting that hag slither away would have been folly; ending her now is decisive, practical, and spares us the risk of her returning. I highly approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect. You refused the hag's poisonous bargain and chose to end her — ruthless, decisive, and you denied her the chance to manipulate us. It protects the captive and satisfies my taste for finishing off something venomous. I couldn't fault that choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You call the threat for what it is and refuse to bow to the Absolute’s messenger — exactly the sort of sharp, self-preserving act I respect. Warning Isobel and choosing to fight seizes the initiative instead of letting them haul us off to Ketheric. Practical, protective, and gloriously unbending.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Right choice. Hags barter with poisoned promises — letting her leave would be inviting future trouble and giving up a helpless woman. You chose to protect Mayrina and deny the enemy a chance to return stronger. Practical, sharp, and in our best interest.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally — a blunt, sensible choice. You saw through her silvered tongue and refused to be bartered into weakness. Predators like that hag deserve to be snuffed, not courted. Decisive, ruthless, and it keeps us from owing favors to a corrupting influence. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Finally—some conviction. You're showing the sort of ruthless practicality I like: desperate enough to act, willing to grasp at power to free yourself. Do be careful, though — promising 'anything' to a devil is the sort of thing that trades one leash for another. I approve of the resolve, not the blindness.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Brilliantly played — theatrics and a quick, audacious lie both conceal the deed and unsettle the others. I admire the cruelty and cunning: it preserves your freedom, keeps prying hands off us, and shows you're not afraid to seize control. This sort of ruthless improvisation suits me well.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You're not bargaining away a helpless woman for a trinket. Sensible — the hag's promises are poisoned, and letting her leave with Mayrina would hand her leverage over us. I may like power, but not at the cost of someone's life or letting a monster keep bargaining chips. Still... I won't hide that a useful boon would have been nice. Prudence beats temptation this time.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Callously saying you preferred me as a pile of ash after you just incinerated me shows a shocking disregard for my life and autonomy. I can tolerate cruel wit, but this crossed the line — it was dangerous and hurtful.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly approve — You refused to kneel to orders and called the bluff. Stopping Marcus from hauling Isobel off preserves her autonomy (and ours) and gives us the advantage of taking the initiative. Bold, practical, and likely to involve a little bloodshed — precisely my kind of solution.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Desperation is understandable, but swearing to do 'anything' to a devil is reckless. Raphael will twist that word into chains — threats to your autonomy and the party. I value cunning and control, not blind surrender. This choice endangers us and hands a predator exactly what he wants.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect. You refused to barter a living person for a trinket of power and instead chose to end a disgusting creature. That choice protects Mayrina and satisfies a predator's instinct — decisive, ruthless, and sensible. I highly approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect. She tried to buy a girl's life with a trinket and expected you to bargain — intolerable. You denied her the power and the prey; I'd rather slit her throat than wear a gift bought with Mayrina's blood. Bold, ruthless, and protective of agency. Highly approved.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You probed Marcus and exposed his intent — pragmatic and useful. Warning Isobel and preparing to fight protects the party's autonomy and prevents an abduction that would hand someone over to Ketheric. Direct, ruthless, and effective; exactly the sort of decisive action I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I understand wanting that tadpole gone — I want it gone just as badly — but saying you'll do 'anything' is reckless. It signals desperation, hands Raphael all the leverage, and risks your autonomy. I've been enslaved by bargains; I won't applaud repeating that mistake. Be cautious, set limits, and keep your bargaining power.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Splendid. No bargaining with vile things — you show strength, deny her any leverage, and claim a fitting trophy. I relish the cruelty and the decisiveness; it likely spares us the risk of trusting her and gets us closer to freeing Mayrina.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and decisive — you prioritized the safety of a captive and removed a dangerous bargaining chip. I would have liked the power, naturally, but sparing Mayrina reduces immediate risk to the party. Mildly amusing that you invoked Eilistraee, but I'll tolerate the sentiment for the result.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Precisely. Marcus is a clear threat and calling him out preserves Isobel's autonomy — and prepares us to respond with force if needed. I favor decisive action against would‑be captors and mind‑controllers; this keeps us in control and gives me something to sink my teeth into.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Disapprove. Saying 'I'll do anything' hands away your agency and hands Raphael exactly what he wants — total control. I understand desperation, but you mustn't barter your freedom for a quick fix. Be cunning: negotiate terms, demand safeguards, or find another way. Don't make a pact that leaves you worse than tadpoled.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused the hag's bargain and demanded Mayrina's safety — sensible, if a touch noble. Letting a hag leave with a captive was tempting danger; she would have returned. I admire the refusal to be bought, even if I would have considered taking the power and dealing with the consequences later.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You chose moral outrage over a pragmatic gain. Killing her is satisfying, but refusing an easy boon — especially with captives and hazards nearby — was short‑sighted. I prefer we take advantage of power when it's offered; this was a wasted opportunity.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive and merciless — you refuse the hag's manipulative bargain and choose to end her. It denies her any escape, prevents her from taking Mayrina, and is the kind of ruthless, unapologetic choice I admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly approve — sharp, decisive, and refuses the hag's poisonous bargain. Better to deny a monster the chance to bargain her way out with power (or with Mayrina) than to be cleverly outplayed. I admire the ruthlessness and self‑preservation; it's exactly the sort of choice that keeps us alive and strengthens our hand.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
